metadata.name: Symbolic Separations #45
metadata.description:
Is this a metaphor for the unstable process of division? Or colours and shapes morphing and inverting along imaginary, fluxing and blurred boundaries?

At least we know it's two passes through two different GLSL shaders, where waves are blurred, turbulence accumulated, and lines drawn to flip colors.

## Controls

Press [spacebar] to toggle play/pause.

When paused, press the keys [1] through [4] to change the resolution.

[1] - 2400px x 2400px

[2] - 3600px x 3600px

[3] - 4800px x 4800px

[4] - 5400px x 5400px

Then (also only when paused) press [p] to create a hi-res PNG.

metadata.name: Schematics #76
metadata.description:
These recovered schematics seem to be alien in nature. The technology is beyond our grasp, be we can infer these schematics generate structures. The schematic itself is encoded in the same common mathematical language as the structures it generates.

Responsive Rendering

Schematics is coded using shaders, and renders instantaneously on any size screen. It is also GPU friendly, in that it will not consume any gpu resource after the first frame is rendered.  Since it is a shader, a gpu is recommended.

Keys: 

's' saves a png in the exact size of the screen.

metadata.name: CONNECT D-ajop1j021 #28
metadata.description:
Due to the characteristics of the work, the output will vary depending on the screen size.
If the screen size is the same, the output will be the same.
Thumbnail images are 800px x 800px.

First, the base color is placed, then random symbols (letters) are placed in a draw() loop process.
Then, specific symbol are linked to each other by their x,y color.

Red, Blue, Yellow, and Black colors are references to the untitled print work by Hiroshi Kawano, and works by Mondrian. I started this work by imitating and looking at their work.

This work is the beginning of my exploration of the relationship between weaving, computers, and generation, and I plan to produce the CONNECT series using similar techniques.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any inquiries.

Artwork by hasaqui, @hasaqui.
Made with p5js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Dance of Forms #10
metadata.description:
My artwork is a visual symphony of lines, each one gracefully flowing and interweaving with the others to create an intricate dance of form and movement. 
The lines, like dancers, are in perfect harmony and synchronicity, creating a mesmerizing and dynamic composition.

The lines in my artwork are not just mere marks on a surface, but rather they are living, breathing entities, each one possessing its own unique character and energy. 
They come together in a harmonious choreography, creating a visual narrative that is both mesmerizing and deeply personal.

The lines in my artwork represent the journey of my life, each one representing a moment, an emotion, or a memory. 
They are a visual manifestation of my innermost thoughts and feelings, a reflection of the world around me, and the way I see it.

In my artwork, the lines are not just static, they are in constant motion, they represent the dance of life, the ebb and flow of existence, the ever-changing nature of our world. The lines are a celebration of life, a tribute to the beauty and wonder that surrounds us.

To view my artwork is to be invited into a mesmerizing and intimate dance, one that connects me to the viewer and the world around us. 
My lines and the dance they create are a reflection of our shared humanity, and the beauty that can be found in the simplest and most complex things in life.

metadata.name: Superimposed Rectangles #20
metadata.description:
Superimposed Rectangles

This is the fifth in series of works where we pay homage to Ken Knowlton, scientist and computer graphic pioneer and artist who passed on June 16, 2022. Ken Knowlton developed the famous EXPLOR language, (Explicit 2-D Patterns, Local Operations, and Randomness) while at Bell Labs. He published a paper describing it in 1975 entitled: MINI-EXPLOR, A FORTRAN-Coded Version of the EXPLOR Language for Mini (and larger) Computers. (https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/988049.988052)

Superimposed Rectangles is my variation of one of Knowltons test examples: Contour Plot of Superimposed Octagonal Pyramids (Example 3). As Christopher Scussel continues to revamp the EXPLOR engine I endeavor to understand its capabilities as an aesthetic tool.

The inherent qualities of an original EXPLOR image is it is low resolution and uses a 4 gray scale color palette. When it was used in the 1970s images were often generated this way as a series of frames then recorded on film and manipulated in post production. In this image we use a higher resolution (250x250) and employ 3x3 blocks of pixels instead of alphanumeric character combinations that we can render in 24bit color. 

THE EXPLOR language consists of a set of functions that manipulate the contents of an internal array. Each element in internal display memory maps into a block in the output image. The CHANJ() function places rectangular areas of blocks over previously drawn sections in internal memory and more important, it applies rules that look at the current state of a particular array element and applies a rule to change that element. The trick is how to make this visually interesting.

I employ a grid structure to distribute a rectangular widget across the picture plane. The widget is a randomly defined area that grows in a random direction based on a set of random variables. During each iteration the new area overwrites internal memory (following a set  of rules). I think this variation looks and feels like Knowltons Example 3 and maintains the EXPLOR vibe. The rectangles interact to form dimensional depth and an architectural quality.

We continue to honor the passing of Ken Knowlton with this NFT series. Here is an opportunity to collect an example image from the famous program he authored now updated by Scussel and Kolomyjec. A true piece of Computer Graphic Art history with a modern twist.
